\section{Brief introduction to programming in R}


\begin{frame}
  \frametitle{S3 and S4 objects}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item The R language has two objects systems, S3 and S4
  \item S3 objects, classes, and methods have been around since the beginning, are informal and interactive.
  \item S3 is really just a naming convention.
    \begin{itemize}
    \item Makes real programmers cringe?
    \end{itemize}
  \item S4 objects, in contract, are newer, formal, less interactive, and still incomplete. Rather difficult.
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
  \frametitle{S3 objects}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Methods for objects of a particular class are called by \texttt{method.class()}
  \item Methods include \texttt{summary()}, \texttt{anova()}, \texttt{print()}, etc.
  \end{itemize}
  
  <<>>=
  x <- 1:10
  y <- rnorm(1.5 + .5*x) 
  @
  \end{frame}


